Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, they reach 29 percent
According to the initial preliminary results, a noticeable weakening of both parties of the grand parties to the grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought the early parliamentary elections in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly harsh losses, where the position of the former chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the edge.
In contrast, the election leader of the alliance is working for the future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider, for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the social democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but it loses 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
The ÖVP performed even worse, which lost almost nine percent of the votes at 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in post-Austrian history, and especially with the People's Party, which had demanded the early elections, this is a really disastrous result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP had left the coalition, the People's Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
The voters, however, have probably punished the party for failing the government.
Already in the initial reactions to the results there was speculation about a possible resignation of the party leader and previous vice-knightly Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be the case on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party executive.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the election debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) received 18 percent, the BZÖ eleven percent of the votes for the time being - at the same time granted the Social Democrats exempt their fear that the year 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had reached collusion with the populists (at the FPÖ was still uniform, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) with a joint government, which had even s.
Jörg Haider, who has already declared, is obviously based on this development, is prepared to cooperate with each party and expects a return to Austrian federal politics.
The Green Party also moved into parliament, which, however, suffered slight losses and slid from the third place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four-percentage hurdle and therefore did not come into parliament.
