The first virtual provider will come to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is nothing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic ones at lower prices.
Perhaps it will not be long in coming.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile providers are working to be the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority 'T', which pointed out that the price of a text message here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - for some customers of the Czech mobile phone providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition, which really makes a challenge.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to swear about the fact that there is a lot of competition on the Czech market.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (T) Pavel Dvorak, who had often said in the past that there is no place for another provider in the Czech Republic, is often also told that there is no place for another provider.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a large number of chances (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies left).
But there is one more possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, which was then also had to react to by the traditional mobile phone providers.
Before the entry of such companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar votes in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don't need to look long for examples.
In February we reported on the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the country's fifth largest provider.
The Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic owns, among other things, is Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can concentrate on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less comprehensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers at least half more cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a fairly good move to rely on a non-clichical target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust them," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
