In 1955, Hurston questioned in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel the request of the Supreme Court to force integration by describing his decision in the Brown case against the school council as "offensive instead of respecting my race."
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group reunion in Eatonville and the self-consciousness of his adolescents.
