William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (25. September) write that "he regained teaching economic history in Oxford in 1946 and was awarded a Houblon-norman research fellowship in 1950... while at the same time he was studying for a BSc, an MA and a doctorate.
This is a conclusion from a certification of authors in Woodruff's book "Beyond Nab End", but it is not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He served in the United States in 1950-1951 as part of a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for good and moved to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
