'Auto-bees' avoiding collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature this time, more precisely, by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight is based on the swarming behaviour of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the accident prevention technologies.
The engineers from the technical development center of the Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&D Brand Management, the BR23C represents an expansion of the four-pous Nissan security shield.
This robot is intended to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid the collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds up its own oval-shaped flight space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the facet-face eyes of the bee, which can see over an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, which allows her to fly undisturbed in their personal airspace without interruption.
In order to recreate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It notices obstacles that are up to two metres at a distance of up to two metres before the BR23C and are within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor, which is directly translated into signals for avoiding the collision
"At the moment when obstacle is noticed, the small robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels around 90o or even larger angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to any other system is that this evasive manoeuvre takes place absolutely instinctively.
If it were not so, the robot might not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles, explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Laboratory of Mobility and the senior engineer of this project.
In contrast to a bee, the robot can neither deviate up or down, but also not covered; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in the infinite directions and infinite way, as the bees make it.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and deceleration functions, so that the small robot avoids the collisions.
"This device needs only every few seconds to process the information and act according to this information.
It does not require neither the information nor the intuitive logic of manoeuvres to be stored, so it can continuously work with only a couple of tens of storage space.
That sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs and not even the MBs of storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan prophesied to introduce to the next decade at the production cars.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite to lead to the goal while driving, avoiding the obstacles on the way.
