The psychology of surpassing - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the filing bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to admit defeat in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play the lottery, while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent's surpassing plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to underpin their thesis, the economists in the research group have also conducted investigations to track money.
In this case, three groups were supposed to be against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was notified of the true value of the product, after which they made their operations.
Another group were also promised 15 dollars reward, in case they emerge from the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis on one winning, while the other was losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the group playing against the "loser" were prepared to attend higher stakes than those in the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any earlier economic theory.
Until now, these have only justified the behaviours observed at auctions with the joy of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was dissolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When is the doctor to see?
Worldwide, around half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated at a hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread to two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, through the digestive tract (for example, by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretions or saliva).
In any case, travelers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are about two-three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice occurs on the skin and eyes, the stool becomes light, urine becomes dark, and recovery can last for two-three weeks.
Worldwide dies around 1 million annually. People in those induced by hepatitis B, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people are in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells insidiously - in many cases, the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more common: those who undergoed a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Detected in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, whereby the risk of infection is banished and prevented the development of cancer.
The 30. September is World Hepatitis Day, and in 2004 is organised by patient representatives worldwide for the first time.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
