This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a visual field of 180 degrees within 2 metres, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the auto robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this manoeuvre takes place purely instinctively.
"If it were not so, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the car robot project.
