The possibility of gaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; it is no coincidence that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of ocean energy was forfeited, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the global energy demand could be covered by the energies generated by the ocean waves.
This would amount to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides would also be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to focus on ocean energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies from the traditional energy sector relying on marine energy production.
"Chevron examines these technologies" – said the spokesperson for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal – and weighs up the opportunity to work with us."
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that is not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil continues to be produced by the United States in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which are investing in the new industry; the details are not known either, so observers speak of increasing interest.
Even more improvements.
Experts speak of a technology that is still on the rise, not least because the last doubts on the part of the environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland have been of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a much greater impact on the environment are required.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the float via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned plant of this kind, which are only waiting for the state permit. Part of the energy generated could also be used for military facilities.
However, Verdant Power already produces energy for a merchandise store and a parking facility using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator due to the resulting rotary motion.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute of Electricity Extraction Research, the potential that lies in the tides deserves particular interest in the present.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of power.
It is precisely the tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
